{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623825"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16874"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16874"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.19,0.04,0.75,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68667"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9564"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54124"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9858"},{"type":"tags","id":"9864"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22593"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68667"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes afterload in the cardiovascular system?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rate of ventricular pressure development","Volume of blood remaining in the ventricle after systole","Amount of blood ejected per heartbeat","Pressure against which the ventricle must contract to eject blood","Force stretching the ventricle during diastolic filling"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPressure against which the ventricle must contract to eject blood\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes afterload. For the left ventricle, this is primarily determined by systemic vascular resistance and aortic pressure. For the right ventricle, pulmonary vascular resistance is the main determinant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolume of blood remaining in the ventricle after systole\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes end-systolic volume, not afterload\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForce stretching the ventricle during diastolic filling\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes preload, which is the initial stretch of cardiac muscle before contraction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERate of ventricular pressure development\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes dP/dt (change in pressure per unit of time), which is a measure of contractility\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmount of blood ejected per heartbeat\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes stroke volume, which is influenced by but not equivalent to afterload\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncreased afterload (such as in hypertension) requires the ventricle to generate more force to maintain cardiac output. This can lead to ventricular hypertrophy over time if the increase is sustained.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Afterload is the pressure that the ventricle must overcome to eject blood during systole.","Increased afterload requires more force generation by the ventricle to maintain cardiac output."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54124"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16874"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54124"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:18:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:19:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9564"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68667"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4903"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cardiac physiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-13T22:30:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T22:30:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup